                            <div class="container">
                    <div class="exc-container">
                        <div class="muscle-text bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                            <h3><b>Latissimus Dorsi </b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Your </span><a href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/329714635_Anatomy_Back_Latissimus_Dorsi" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">latissimus dorsi</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, also known as your lats, make up the majority of your back musculature. They are primarily responsible for shoulder extension, adduction, and internal rotation. This means bringing your arm down, across your body, and into your body.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">During the straight-arm lat pulldown, they extend your shoulders to bring the cable closer to your body. As the only primary mover, the straight arm pulldown is an excellent exercise to isolate your latissimus dorsi muscles.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Studies looking at EMG data provide insight into the extent to which certain exercises target specific muscle groups. This exercise significantly engages the latissimus dorsi, especially when using a wider grip on the bar. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Muscle activation rates have been shown to reach approximately </span><a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2076-3417/12/21/11138" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">20% of maximum voluntary contraction</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> (MVC). This represents the highest activation rate out of the primary movers.</span></p>                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                                        <section class="exc-secondary">
                <div class="container">
                    <div class="exc-container bd-bot">
                        <div class="muscle-title">
