                            <div class="container">
                    <div class="exc-container">
                        <div class="muscle-text bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                            <h3><b>Posterior Deltoid</b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537056/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">posterior deltoid</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is the muscle located at the back of the shoulder. It’s responsible for shoulder extension and internal rotation. This means bringing the arms back and into the body. Although the straight-arm lat pulldown primarily targets the lats, the posterior deltoid is also engaged. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The posterior deltoid stabilizes the shoulder during the exercise and extends the arms while pulling down on the bar. These factors contribute to the straight arm lat pulldown’s effectiveness as a shoulder strengthener. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">As a secondary mover, it’s not as involved as the latissimus dorsi muscles. However, with a supporting role, it does get a smaller muscle-building stimulus as a stabilizer muscle. </span></p><h3><b>Triceps Long Heads</b><b> </b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK536996/#:~:text=Long%20head%20%E2%80%94The%20origin%20of%20the%20long%20head,head%20of%20the%20humerus%20in%20the%20glenoid%20cavity" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">triceps long head</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is the largest tricep muscle, which sits beneath the posterior deltoid. It primarily performs elbow extension and assists in shoulder stabilization. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">During the straight arm lat pulldown, it keeps the elbow extended as you bring the weight back. It isometrically contacts which means it stays still as your limb moves. In this case, your tricep contracts while your arm extends at the shoulder joint.</span></p>                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
